**W3-D3-Models**

**Today you learn:**
- Creating a model (database table as a Python class)
- Migrations — turning model into actual database table

---

**1. Create the model**

`blog/models.py`:
```python
from django.db import models

class Post(models.Model):  # inherits from models.Model, not a normal class
    title = models.CharField(max_length=200)     # short text field
    content = models.TextField()                  # long text field
    created_at = models.DateTimeField(auto_now_add=True)  # auto-fills date when created

    def __str__(self):
        return self.title  # controls how object shows in admin/shell
```

---

**2. Run migrations — this creates the actual database table**

```bash
python manage.py makemigrations   # creates migration file describing the change
python manage.py migrate          # applies that change to the database
```

```text
# makemigrations = "write down what changed"
# migrate = "actually apply it to the database"
# always run both, in this order, every time you change models.py
```

---

**3. Check it worked — Django shell**

```bash
python manage.py shell
```

```python
from blog.models import Post

p1 = Post(title="My First Post", content="Hello Django")
p1.save()   # saves this object as a row in the database

Post.objects.all()   # shows all rows in the Post table
```

